European food inflation slipped
The accelerating inflation rate in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The November price increase was higher than expected in 13 euro area countries, with annual inflation of 3.1% following the October 2.6%, reported the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the European Union.
The official forecast was only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the basic rate, unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, saying that a reduction would lead to an inflation spiral, coupled with rising raw material prices and easing unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below 2%, but close to that.
One analyst said the ECB is in the twenty-second trap: "We need to talk down" inflation so that we don't have to act on it later.
In Germany, the November inflation rate of 3.3 percent was a 12-year record; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has been driven by rising food and energy prices.
The yields of grain increased by 88 percent, and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Food and milk products were also subject to substantial increases in 2007.
The global market price of crude oil has increased 52 percent this year, and last month, it cost nearly $100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 to 2.5% this year in 2008 but will decline to 1.9 in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3% over the next three to four months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1%.
However, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
