In many places, disinfectants are being used to save money
This year, more than a thousand infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in hospitals, the density of beds, the overload of staff are not conducive to stopping infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, they also save on disinfectants.
They just diagnosed MRSA infection in the trauma department at St. John's Hospital.
A man who was involved in a serious accident was shown to have antibiotic resistant bacteria.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred earlier this year.
A seriously injured man in a car accident was released from the hospital, but soon afterward he had to return with MRSA infection, and an important surgery was not performed since because of a bacterium in his system.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Center, Böröcz Karolina.
That means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens are probably registered in hospitals, the rest are unknown.
About two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) are well-responsive to antibiotics and well curable.
However, when antibiotics are used in excess or improperly, a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics develops a highly antibiotic resistant bacterium that spreads rapidly under inappropriate hospital conditions.
In particular, temporary or permanent immune system malfunction can cause serious hospital infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning - sepsis - in weakened, elderly or low-weight patients.
According to the medical director of St. John's Hospital, MRSA infections are not unusual, and they are a common practice in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not there, Nyulasi Tibor said, where the presence of the pathogen is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate such patients, nurse staff treat them with rubber gloves and masks, and they have the right antibiotics to treat them", said Nyulasi Tibor.
Patients admitted to hospital are tested for MRSA in their bodies, but this does not always prevent infection.
Not a fashion sample
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current domestic hospital conditions and conditions are not favourable to prevent the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Böröcz Karolina.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals, nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients entering and patients carrying MRSA should be isolated immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these studies.
Most cases are then exposed when a patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the chief medical officer of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and national guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always follow this.
Microbiological samples are even less common in the communicable and basic care, Böröcz Karolina said.
Save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another through medical personnel.
So there's a very big role to play in handwashing, gloves, wearing a mask, but there are also significant gaps in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by drop infection, contact, but in home hospital conditions, isolation of the infected patient is not always possible.
In fact, hospitals were often crowded, often with beds very close together, even though patients should be at least 1.5 metres apart from each other from an epidemiological point of view.
Unfortunately, it is also true, Böröcz Karolina noted, that in hospitals in poor financial conditions, disinfectants are being saved, there are few nurses, many patients, and so the chances of infections are even higher.
Böröcz Karolina said that where appropriate precautions are taken, there may be fewer such infections or the spread of the pathogen could be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is costing health insurers enormous amounts of money, and they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government programme included the prevention and reduction of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful and, based on the data reported, there is a decreasing trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has priorities in preventing the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
