Political Capital: Hungarian Guard raised the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded in August this year with the support of the Jobbik Hungary Movement, have raised the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital.
The company's "cocktail warning" stated that the biggest political risk to the Hungarian Guard is that "the ethnic tensions between the Hungarian Gypsy and non-Gypsy population may escalate into violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is likely to be aimed at provoking such an action, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this can be traced to one of the main failures of Hungarian politicians: "the public debate on Roma has been handed over to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who could build a political strategy against Gypsy-Hungarian".
This, they believe, deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, the research institute notes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, due to the large domestic and international media attention, "have significantly undermined the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of its stability and its faith in democratic development".
It is recalled that since the autumn of 2006, as part of the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which has received increasing publicity and momentum, more than one organisation, calling itself a "national self-defense" association, has been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007.
"The common feature of these compilations is that they define themselves as a civilian organization while openly proclaiming their members' - even armed - preparation for defense (disaster protection, homeland security, law enforcement) tasks, and also citing the inadequacy of the police, the military, or the state", they added.
They noted that this was done in accordance with the methodology which seeks to place different political endeavours in civilian dress based on the political and non-partisan nature of society.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association are therefore not only a means of avoiding legal errors in the court record for these associations, but also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor for neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, several neighbouring states have also cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of danger, and some neighbouring countries' ultra-nationalist political actors want to justify their anti-Hungarian policies by referring to the establishment of the Hungarian Guard.
All this will affect the political stability of the region.'
According to the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern and Central Europe, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
As they wrote, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The Bulgarian Guard was formed in the wake of the mass Roma riots that broke out in a district of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana).
The BNU took advantage of this and decided to establish the guard, saying that the organisation's aim was 'national self-defense'.
They say that Bulgaria has experienced "gypsy terror" for the past 17 years, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, Political Capital recalls.
It was added that the initiative provoked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As they wrote, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced that they are setting up their own guard as a resistance.
As the Hungarian Guard's operations so far bear similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be ruled out that the Romani people in Hungary will respond to the threat by organising their own self-defense, as stated in the risk warning of Political Capital.
Juhász Attila, Director of Research at Political Capital, said that the risk analysis was one of the activities of the research institute.
As you said, they publish their risk analysis every year and if they experience something that could affect the change in risk, they inform the public, as in this case by issuing a risk warning.
