The most depressing memories
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen archive has been made public, documenting the fate of the 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archival documents, which cover 27 kilometres of shelf space in Bad Arolsen, Hessen, have so far been searchable only for "humanitarian" purposes, providing unique and nominal insight for the victims or their descendants.
Eleven archival governments - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open the archive to researchers and historians.
After all states ratified the treaty, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen Archives allows historians to conduct research "on the relocation of prisoners, the health of camp residents and forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive run by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
To date, several states, including Germany, have opposed the publication of the documents, as they contain names and thus confidential information.
For example, some deported victims may have suspected homosexuality or a mental disability.
After the war, the Gestapo began collecting the lists of concentration camps and arrest warrants for practical purposes, to search for deported or sentenced civilians for forced labor and, possibly, to provide evidence of their internment, which could be used to pay compensation.
Bad Arolsen currently has more than 300 permanent staff working on tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, some of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of great importance.
"These documents are basically nothing new", said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
