Congress approves the adoption of MiFID, which took effect on November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary debate - which ended today with a congressional vote to approve the Senate amendments - the government has launched a social dialogue on the legislation underlying the law so that both can be implemented before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts made by the Members and the Senators in negotiating and agreeing the most favourable investor protection norms and detailed regulation of companies' activities in order to ensure efficient market functioning.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, enables the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, extending the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new Directive will enable financial advisory services to be provided to firms, both natural and legal, and will create a new financial service provider company (ESIS) form, namely financial advisory companies (AFI), alongside securities trading companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the Act increases the number of systems suitable for carrying out transactions involving funds, including multilateral trading platforms and order-performance internalisation systems in competition with current market players.
The Act also requires investment firms to provide market information on the aspects that determine their business profile, risk-taking and risk management methods, and to keep records of all transactions carried out to facilitate the verification of the CNMV.
The Economic Committee of Congress has introduced a number of amendments, the most important of which is that securitised debt is treated as a "complex" financial instrument because of the high risk posed to the investor.
On the other hand, the transposition of the Directive has also been used to legally outline the scope of activity of those with business and entrepreneurial qualifications, 30 years after the Royal Decree establishing professional functions for economists only came into force in 1977.
The Senate also proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as an intermediary agent working for another account, not requiring CNMV's authorisation and able to sell products to or acquire customers to several investment firms at the same time.
