The climate of Venus may provide a glimpse into the future of the Earth
Scientists have concluded that Venus once provided pleasant living conditions.
Data from a European orbiting spacecraft suggests that this planet is much more of Earth's dangerous twin brother than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are about the same size and orbit, although Venus is located a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now know that billions of years ago, life on Venus could have been very similar to that on Earth, and it could have even been habitable.
However, due to the extreme greenhouse effect of carbon dioxide, the atmospheric erosion caused by solar radiation, and the planet's slower rotation, Venus has entered a completely different evolutionary path.
Today, the planet's water has evaporated, its surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and hurricane winds and lightning storms are destroying it.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft - based on a year of studying the planet - paint a vivid picture of how similar catastrophic climate changes could develop on Earth.
Fred Taylor, professor of physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming clear why the climate of Venus is so different from that of Earth, even though the two planets are very similar in structure.
"Our new data has enabled us to develop a scenario of how Venus formed billions of years ago, when it could have had habitable conditions similar to Earth.
