The prehistory is a long and complicated, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial displays.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxait" in New York City in 1964, painted murals based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" soap powder box.
At a 1968 exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet, with Warhol's consent, hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes were unveiled: these (for cost-saving reasons) were not from Warhol but were shipped directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It wasn't artwork, it was templates, simple exhibits.
However, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo villages in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the day now speak in circles of fifteen boxes that were then authenticated as Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box under the "Stockholm-type" designation and entered the history of art and auction.
Some of them were sold for over $100,000.
The problem, however, is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred walls were made and displayed in wheels in Sweden, which he left to Warhol.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 for a St. Petersburg exhibition in Malmö.
But by this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the chief curator of the Moderna Museet, also examined three Swedish private-owned boxes, including three Brillo Boxes, which were made in Stockholm in 1968.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the plating without a foundation, with a painting loop, and that it was not oil but acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authenticated by the artist, and should therefore be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo Boxes", says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet. "The Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York will not rule otherwise, and Moderna Museet will select the six boxes in its collection as copy/exhibition material".
